subSubSection.paragraph:
ETYMOLOGY: ktenos + mastax (Gr., f.), comb­jaw; referring to the comblike arrangement of the marginal teeth of this lizard;
parvus
(L.), meaning ‘‘little.’’

The parietal table is roughly trapezoidal, and the dorsal surface is weakly ornamented anteriorly with rugosities, as on the frontals. The maximum width of the parietal table is anteriorly at the frontoparietal suture and the minimum width at the posterior margin (slightly wider than half the width at the frontoparietal suture); therefore, the parietal table has no obvious constriction at the middle level. However, the parietal laterally develops a relatively deep flange, indicating a dorsal origin of the temporal muscle. As a distinct character of the species, the posterior margin of the table is symmetrically notched for the insertion of dorsal axial musculature (
spinalis capitis
). The supratemporal process of the parietal is slightly longer than the table and extends posterolaterally at a roughly 45° angle in relation to the midline of the skull. The process is strongly compressed laterally, having a dorsal crest and a deeply sloped lateral surface for attachment of temporal muscles.
